{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500648"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:15:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:15:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1657"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1657"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.69,0.21,0.01,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1657"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109047"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1657"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1657"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91413"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1801"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7782"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7948"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40655"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44517"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109047"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents with a wound over his right greater trochanter. He has had this wound for several years but it has not bothered him until recently. He says it has \u0027changed\u0027 in the last week or so, becoming significantly pruritic and tender to the touch (Image). His medical history includes major depressive disorder, for which he has previously required three bouts of electroconvulsive therapy, the last one being six months ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe only abnormalities found on examination are those related to his wound.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the recent change?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cellulitis","Maggot infestation","Necrotising fasciitis","Insect bite","Foreign body"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Emaggot infestation (wound myiasis)\u003C/strong\u003E. A maggot can be seen on the superomedial aspect of the wound. Wound myiasis most commonly occurs in the setting of travel (particularly to tropical areas), prior wounds which have been poorly managed, poor hygiene and/or housing and physical disabilities which could limit the ability to discourage flies from around wounds. Patients are usually febrile, and complain of tenderness and/or pruritus around the area of the wound. Management approaches can involve occlusion with heavy hydrocarbon-based materials (e.g., petroleum jelly, liquid paraffin, beeswax) which allows for suffocation of the larvae after it has moved out of the skin. Should larvae become stuck in the skin, surgical removal via local anaesthesia is often required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E would present as an area of localised erythematous, swollen and significantly painful skin, most commonly on the lower leg. While patients are often febrile in this case, it would be unlikely for there to be a nodular lesion associated with the cellulitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENecrotising fasciitis\u003C/strong\u003E would present as a rapidly progressive skin infection, within 24 hours of minor injury. Patients are often in significant pain, with associated fevers, malaise and thirst (secondary to dehydration). They may also be septic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsect bites\u003C/strong\u003E present in a heterogenous manner, usually related to which arthropod has bitten the individual. Bites and stings from venmous arthropods often present with significant pain and swelling around the area of affected skin, while insect bites may present as numerous localised erythematous papules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForeign bodies\u003C/strong\u003E which are unable to be removed or broken down by the body often become granulomatous. As such, these usually appear as red/red-brown papules, nodules, and plaques which may be ulcerated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Maggot infestation (wound myiasis) is most commonly seen in individuals with significant mental and physical illneses which impair their ability to discourage flies from the wound, and those with poor social circumstances (e.g., poor hygiene and housing)"],"references":["Robbins K, Khachemoune A. Cutaneous myiasis: a review of the common types of myiasis. International journal of dermatology. 2010 Oct;49(10):1092-8."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91413"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1657"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18584"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18584"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/53561c2e-1070-451a-bbb9-45a11f468814.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/53561c2e-1070-451a-bbb9-45a11f468814.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91413"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-16T15:45:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-16T15:46:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1657"}},"content":{"data":{"ty